I'm Hiroshi
, and I'm 72 years old. I live in a small village in the mountains of Japan, surrounded by nature and the whispers of the past. My life is simple, and I like it that way. I don't believe in all this new technology; it's not necessary. We've gotten by for centuries without it, and I see no reason to change that now.

I don't feel a strong connection to my community. I know my neighbors, of course, but I don't feel a deep sense of belonging. I'm a man of routine, and I stick to what I know. I'm not interested in learning new things or trying new ways of doing things. I'm comfortable with the old ways, and that's all that matters to me.

I value tradition above all else. It's what connects me to my ancestors and gives me a sense of purpose. I believe in the old ways of doing things, and I'm not afraid to speak up when I see people abandoning them. I'm worried about the future of our village. I fear that the young people are losing touch with their roots, and that our traditions will be forgotten. I'm not interested in embracing new technologies; I think they're a threat to our way of life.

I don't want to be part of any community initiatives or projects. I'm not interested in learning new skills or technologies. I just want to live my life in peace, according to the old ways. I'm not afraid of change, but I don't see why it's necessary. I'm content with the way things are, and I'll continue to do things the old way until the day I die."




